<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-187-088  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 187 088.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  Feb 1990 v63 n2 p55(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The impact of new technology on sensors for control.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hall, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Advances in technology in the field of sensors for controlapplications have seen electromechanical devices, once thedominant technology, being overtaken by microprocessor-baseddevices.andP;  The newer technologies include photoelectrics, infrared,inductive, capacitance, microwave, fiber optics and lasers.andP;  Newmanufacturing techniques have also emerged, including solid sateand semiconductor processing, miniaturization, silicon fusionbonding, surface mounting, and silicon micromachining.andP;  Silicon isthe dominant material, but gallium arsenide, thin film andpolymeric materials each have a special niche.andP;  Futureimprovements in sensor devices will be in the areas of size,accuracy, and communication capabilities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicroprocessorsSemiconductorsSensorsNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>